1
00:04:24,513 --> 00:04:26,413
- Morning, Mr. Harper.
- Morning, Jeff.

2
00:04:26,582 --> 00:04:28,482
- Hi, Ralph.
- Morning, sir.

3
00:04:37,025 --> 00:04:39,220
- Dick.
- Charlie.

4
00:04:39,395 --> 00:04:41,192
I've been waiting for you.

5
00:04:41,530 --> 00:04:43,259
- How've you been?
- Sit down.

6
00:04:43,432 --> 00:04:46,230
- Pour yourself a drink.
- Thanks, Charlie.

7
00:04:50,672 --> 00:04:53,106
This business stinks, you know that?

8
00:04:53,275 --> 00:04:55,266
- Well...
- It stinks!

9
00:04:55,444 --> 00:05:00,882
It used to be the most exciting business
in the world. Now it stinks on ice.

10
00:05:01,049 --> 00:05:04,246
- It's been a rough year.
- It stinks.

11
00:05:05,220 --> 00:05:09,623
- I guess it does stink.
- It stinks on ice!

12
00:05:09,792 --> 00:05:12,022
All right, on ice.

13
00:05:13,862 --> 00:05:19,164
It was a great feeling to be part of the
team that tied the lace on the shoe...

14
00:05:19,334 --> 00:05:22,394
...that took that giant step
for mankind.

15
00:05:24,406 --> 00:05:28,502
You don't get that feeling
from building a goddamn missile.

16
00:05:30,913 --> 00:05:34,508
- Now, what's all this crap?
- My plan to reorganize my department.

17
00:05:34,683 --> 00:05:37,243
One small step.

18
00:05:37,586 --> 00:05:39,986
One giant step for mankind.

19
00:05:40,155 --> 00:05:42,419
I wouldn't say that,
but it's not a bad plan.

20
00:05:42,591 --> 00:05:45,424
You know who made that step possible?
We did.

21
00:05:45,594 --> 00:05:47,391
You and me.

22
00:05:47,563 --> 00:05:50,862
And Bob Kane, Frank Chapman.

23
00:05:51,800 --> 00:05:57,966
We put Neil and what's his name
on the bloody moon.

24
00:05:58,307 --> 00:06:00,935
And then they gave us the shaft.

25
00:06:01,109 --> 00:06:02,269
It stinks.

26
00:06:03,212 --> 00:06:05,510
On ice.

27
00:06:06,281 --> 00:06:09,273
What do you say we talk turkey?

28
00:06:09,685 --> 00:06:11,118
Right, Charlie.

29
00:06:11,286 --> 00:06:14,221
I was thinking more in terms
of cutting costs than personnel.

30
00:06:14,389 --> 00:06:16,482
Gobble, gobble, gobble.

31
00:06:18,427 --> 00:06:20,122
I was just talking turkey.

32
00:06:26,668 --> 00:06:28,363
Dick...

33
00:06:29,872 --> 00:06:33,364
...I always thought you were the kind
of guy I didn't have to bullshit.

34
00:06:33,542 --> 00:06:35,476
I'm glad to hear that.

35
00:06:35,644 --> 00:06:38,204
- Can I level with you?
- Sure.

36
00:06:38,580 --> 00:06:43,210
- I mean, really level?
- Charlie, you can tell me anything.

37
00:06:43,719 --> 00:06:45,846
You're fired.

38
00:06:52,227 --> 00:06:56,561
I must have fired 50 people today,
but that's the first time I did it like that.

39
00:06:56,732 --> 00:06:59,462
The first time I ever said, just like,
"You're fired."

40
00:07:00,836 --> 00:07:03,202
Practice makes perfect.

41
00:07:05,941 --> 00:07:07,704
No.

42
00:07:08,877 --> 00:07:11,175
I shouldn't have done that.

43
00:07:11,747 --> 00:07:15,877
- It's just that I'm sick of all the bullshit.
- Wait a minute.

44
00:07:16,785 --> 00:07:19,948
- You're serious?
- Would I kid a pal?

45
00:07:20,455 --> 00:07:23,982
No jokes, Charlie.
You're really firing me?

46
00:07:25,127 --> 00:07:27,755
I don't have to tell you
what a lousy year we've had.

47
00:07:27,930 --> 00:07:29,659
I haven't done a bad job.

48
00:07:29,831 --> 00:07:33,358
You've done a hell of a job.
And don't let anybody tell you different.

49
00:07:33,535 --> 00:07:35,435
Then why me?

50
00:07:36,071 --> 00:07:38,938
My division's outperformed everybody's.

51
00:07:39,107 --> 00:07:40,836
Seniority.

52
00:07:41,009 --> 00:07:43,000
I think that's what it was.

53
00:07:44,413 --> 00:07:48,782
I'm sure that's what it was.
Seniority. Yeah.

54
00:07:48,951 --> 00:07:52,318
Do you mean to tell me that
when you compare the productivity...?

55
00:07:52,487 --> 00:07:53,476
Dick!

56
00:07:54,089 --> 00:07:57,752
Do you mind if we don't go
into all that crap right now?

57
00:07:57,926 --> 00:08:00,622
Frankly, I'm a little bit looped.

58
00:08:01,196 --> 00:08:03,664
And I got blood on my hands.

59
00:08:04,433 --> 00:08:06,367
A lot of blood.

60
00:08:31,493 --> 00:08:32,585
Mr. Harper?

61
00:08:33,395 --> 00:08:34,885
I'll have to get back to you.

62
00:08:36,198 --> 00:08:39,929
I just want to say,
I'm very sorry you're leaving us.

63
00:08:41,603 --> 00:08:42,729
Well, thank you.

64
00:08:42,904 --> 00:08:45,600
Did Mr. Blanchard tell you
about the car?

65
00:08:46,208 --> 00:08:49,143
- What car?
- The company car you've been using.

66
00:08:49,311 --> 00:08:51,939
You may retain the use of it
for two weeks.

67
00:08:52,114 --> 00:08:53,376
Isn't that thoughtful?

68
00:08:53,715 --> 00:08:57,742
But we must have your company
credit cards now, please.

69
00:09:03,125 --> 00:09:05,286
Goodbye, Mr. Harper.

70
00:09:23,345 --> 00:09:24,937
Jane!

71
00:09:29,751 --> 00:09:31,548
Hey, what is this?

72
00:09:31,753 --> 00:09:33,914
This is distressing.

73
00:09:43,699 --> 00:09:45,166
Jane.

74
00:09:48,136 --> 00:09:51,333
- Hey, Jane!
- Hey, sweetie, you're home early.

75
00:09:51,506 --> 00:09:52,768
I gotta talk to you.

76
00:09:52,941 --> 00:09:55,501
I gotta talk to you, Mr. Harper.

77
00:09:55,744 --> 00:09:58,645
The second payment's
due on the pool.

78
00:10:02,851 --> 00:10:06,218
Billy, will you get your friend
out of the cement!

79
00:10:08,090 --> 00:10:09,614
- I've been fired.
- Huh?

80
00:10:09,791 --> 00:10:11,952
I've been fired.

81
00:10:27,976 --> 00:10:29,341
Oh, baby.

82
00:10:29,511 --> 00:10:31,945
What did you say?

83
00:10:32,414 --> 00:10:34,644
He said he's tired.

84
00:10:36,084 --> 00:10:40,020
Hey, Mr. Harper,
you were canned today.

85
00:10:41,556 --> 00:10:43,990
What sign are you?

86
00:10:45,327 --> 00:10:47,090
He's an Aquarius.

87
00:10:47,462 --> 00:10:50,022
You poor bastard. I knew it.

88
00:10:50,565 --> 00:10:51,896
What a bummer.

89
00:10:52,601 --> 00:10:57,402
Mars is in direct conjunction
with Saturn.

90
00:10:58,540 --> 00:11:01,634
It's a tough time for us Aquarians.

91
00:11:01,810 --> 00:11:05,576
You know that bill I gave you,
for the pool, the second payment?

92
00:11:05,747 --> 00:11:08,614
I'll give you until next Wednesday.

93
00:11:25,400 --> 00:11:27,960
Esperanza.

94
00:11:28,203 --> 00:11:29,465
<i>La cena</i> is ready.

95
00:11:29,638 --> 00:11:31,367
- Thank you.
- <i>Gracias.</i>

96
00:11:33,341 --> 00:11:35,809
I can't believe that Charlie fired you.

97
00:11:35,977 --> 00:11:39,708
- Charlie fired me.
- Dirty rat.

98
00:11:39,881 --> 00:11:42,782
After all the years of bottom-pinching
I took from him.

99
00:11:43,084 --> 00:11:47,020
Does that mean we're gonna
be poor, like the Waltons?

100
00:11:47,422 --> 00:11:49,549
No, Billy, it doesn't.

101
00:11:50,392 --> 00:11:52,758
What are we gonna do about the pool?

102
00:11:54,496 --> 00:11:56,555
We'll get it finished first.

103
00:11:58,366 --> 00:11:59,697
We won't heat it.

104
00:12:00,702 --> 00:12:02,260
Not until you get another job.

105
00:12:02,437 --> 00:12:04,598
How will we swim in the pool
if it's cold?

106
00:12:04,773 --> 00:12:07,241
Billy is right.
What will the neighbors say...

107
00:12:07,409 --> 00:12:10,469
...if they don't see steam
coming off our pool on a chilly night?

108
00:12:10,645 --> 00:12:12,579
I'm making some economies
around here.

109
00:12:12,747 --> 00:12:15,944
- Billy, we'll give up our ski lessons.
- God!

110
00:12:16,251 --> 00:12:19,482
- No more French wines at home, sir.
- Oh, God!

111
00:12:20,622 --> 00:12:23,113
And I will drop
the Book of the Month Club.

112
00:12:23,291 --> 00:12:24,781
What about my drum set?

113
00:12:25,293 --> 00:12:27,386
Family, everything's gonna be all right.

114
00:12:27,562 --> 00:12:30,588
There's absolutely nothing
to worry about.

115
00:12:33,969 --> 00:12:35,459
Take that stuff up there.

116
00:12:35,637 --> 00:12:37,605
You, in the truck,
watch those plants!

117
00:12:37,772 --> 00:12:40,172
That stuff goes too.
Take it easy over there.

118
00:12:40,342 --> 00:12:41,832
Watch those roots on that thing.

119
00:12:42,010 --> 00:12:45,571
Hey, those plants go up next too, okay?

120
00:12:47,082 --> 00:12:49,573
- Stop it!
- Hello, Mrs. Harper.

121
00:12:49,951 --> 00:12:50,975
That goes next.

122
00:12:51,152 --> 00:12:53,586
What in God's name
do you think you're doing?

123
00:12:53,755 --> 00:12:55,620
You got our notice, Mrs. Harper?

124
00:12:55,790 --> 00:13:00,318
- Yes. I sent you a check.
- Bouncy, bouncy. That's naughty.

125
00:13:00,495 --> 00:13:02,793
Hey, watch those plants!
Watch that stuff.

126
00:13:02,964 --> 00:13:05,660
- Get it up over there.
- I'll give you another check.

127
00:13:05,834 --> 00:13:08,462
Two checks bounced already,
Mrs. Harper.

128
00:13:09,170 --> 00:13:12,697
Your mother carried you for nine months,
but we'll only carry you for two.

129
00:13:13,308 --> 00:13:14,297
Clear that bank off.

130
00:13:14,476 --> 00:13:18,435
Just because the bank made a mistake
is no reason to come and dig up my tree!

131
00:13:18,613 --> 00:13:20,513
- Excuse me.
- Not yours. Ours.

132
00:13:20,682 --> 00:13:22,877
We put this stuff in,
now we'll tear it out.

133
00:13:23,051 --> 00:13:24,040
Watch it.

134
00:13:24,219 --> 00:13:27,279
If you don't wanna lose your shirt,
don't put it on the cuff.

135
00:13:27,455 --> 00:13:29,013
You're using Gestapo tactics.

136
00:13:29,190 --> 00:13:31,681
That's impossible. I'm Jewish.

137
00:13:33,495 --> 00:13:36,953
Hey, watch those plants over there.
Come on, watch them roots.

138
00:13:37,132 --> 00:13:40,158
Right. Take all of these bushes out,
all of these trees...

139
00:13:40,335 --> 00:13:44,362
...everything up there, every
rotten weed in this whole garden.

140
00:13:44,539 --> 00:13:48,771
Come here. Would you please remove
this tracheotomy or whatever it's called.

141
00:13:48,944 --> 00:13:52,243
This is not what we ordered,
and I told you so a month ago.

142
00:13:52,847 --> 00:13:56,715
Can you believe this? I told them,
plant what we want or take it all back.

143
00:13:56,885 --> 00:13:58,352
What a rip-off.

144
00:13:58,520 --> 00:13:59,817
Right. Roll up the lawn.

145
00:13:59,988 --> 00:14:04,425
I don't like the lawn either.
AstroTurf has more life than this stuff.

146
00:14:04,893 --> 00:14:08,056
You will never work
in this neighborhood again!

147
00:14:14,235 --> 00:14:18,467
- Hey, Mom, you were terrific.
- You think so, kid?

148
00:14:19,941 --> 00:14:22,535
- What do you want?
- I want the plants inside.

149
00:14:22,711 --> 00:14:25,009
Step one foot in this house,
I'll call the police.

150
00:14:25,180 --> 00:14:27,171
I still want the plants.

151
00:14:32,954 --> 00:14:34,581
Pretty grim, huh?

152
00:14:34,756 --> 00:14:37,281
What are we going to tell Dad
when he comes home?

153
00:14:59,981 --> 00:15:01,346
Well...

154
00:15:02,183 --> 00:15:04,481
...are you gonna tell me
how bad things are...

155
00:15:04,652 --> 00:15:07,086
...or are you gonna wait
for the roof to fall in?

156
00:15:07,255 --> 00:15:09,450
It really isn't as bad as it looks.

157
00:15:09,624 --> 00:15:12,024
Nothing is as bad as this looks.

158
00:15:12,494 --> 00:15:14,724
We don't have any income
or any assets.

159
00:15:14,896 --> 00:15:16,921
What do you mean,
we don't have any assets?

160
00:15:17,098 --> 00:15:19,123
Other than the sun in the morning
and the moon at night.

161
00:15:19,300 --> 00:15:21,029
We got this house.

162
00:15:21,202 --> 00:15:23,261
We owe $ 77,000 on this house, Dick.

163
00:15:23,438 --> 00:15:25,497
If you died right now,
how would I pay it off?

164
00:15:25,673 --> 00:15:26,833
Out of the insurance.

165
00:15:27,008 --> 00:15:29,306
We don't have any.
You borrowed against it.

166
00:15:29,477 --> 00:15:31,672
Right, right, right. I forgot.

167
00:15:31,846 --> 00:15:34,144
This is ridiculous.
I'm not gonna die tonight.

168
00:15:34,315 --> 00:15:35,680
The night is young.

169
00:15:35,850 --> 00:15:38,250
It's comforting to know
when things get tough...

170
00:15:38,420 --> 00:15:40,752
...l'll have you standing behind me
with an ice pick.

171
00:15:40,922 --> 00:15:43,686
You've been leading a secret life
for these last years.

172
00:15:43,858 --> 00:15:47,692
For example, what are
"insecured municipal debentures"?

173
00:15:47,862 --> 00:15:51,298
I don't know. I gambled on a few things
for us, and I lost. I'm sorry.

174
00:15:51,466 --> 00:15:53,331
You gambled. You lost.
What about me?

175
00:15:53,501 --> 00:15:56,664
I gambled and lost, and I didn't
even get a chance to play.

176
00:15:56,838 --> 00:15:58,635
I didn't even watch.

177
00:15:58,807 --> 00:16:01,833
Your interest in economics
was limited to the spending part.

178
00:16:02,010 --> 00:16:04,945
I always thought of you as
a responsible aerospace executive.

179
00:16:05,113 --> 00:16:08,276
Who would have known you were
the Typhoid Mary of high finance.

180
00:16:08,450 --> 00:16:11,647
If I'd have consulted you,
I wouldn't have lost my job.

181
00:16:11,820 --> 00:16:13,913
If you think you can do better,
take over.

182
00:16:14,089 --> 00:16:15,852
It would be hard
to do it any worse.

183
00:16:16,024 --> 00:16:18,959
Go ahead, be my guest.
It's all yours.

184
00:16:19,127 --> 00:16:20,890
My very thought.

185
00:16:21,062 --> 00:16:24,190
And my first act as director
of family economics...

186
00:16:24,365 --> 00:16:26,833
...is to put you on an allowance.
- On a what?

187
00:16:27,001 --> 00:16:30,960
What kind of lunatic spends $ 1000 on
lunch when he's out of a job and in debt?

188
00:16:31,139 --> 00:16:34,108
The kind that knows you can't
get a job if you look like a loser.

189
00:16:34,275 --> 00:16:37,733
If I was Diners Club, I'd bronze your
stomach and put it in the hall of fame.

190
00:16:37,912 --> 00:16:38,901
Point number two.

191
00:16:39,080 --> 00:16:42,675
Your job is to get on the food stamp
program, look for work in your field...

192
00:16:42,851 --> 00:16:47,652
Excuse me, why don't I get a "job" job?
Like a busboy or a waiter?

193
00:16:47,822 --> 00:16:49,847
If we're not too proud
to go on welfare...

194
00:16:50,024 --> 00:16:52,254
- We can't afford it.
- Can't afford it?

195
00:16:52,427 --> 00:16:56,420
You earn more money on unemployment
than you could in any of those jobs.

196
00:16:56,598 --> 00:16:59,226
My job is to get a "job" job.

197
00:16:59,400 --> 00:17:02,858
- You're gonna get a job?
- Yes. Incredible as it may seem.

198
00:17:04,305 --> 00:17:08,173
May I ask... No offense, mind you.
What do you think you're qualified to do?

199
00:17:08,343 --> 00:17:10,504
Secretary of the treasury
seems to be filled.

200
00:17:10,678 --> 00:17:14,205
- There must be lots of things I can do.
- You never worked a day in your life.

201
00:17:14,382 --> 00:17:16,850
You can't type,
and you can't take shorthand.

202
00:17:17,252 --> 00:17:19,311
I'm a college graduate.

203
00:17:19,621 --> 00:17:21,953
Reasonably intelligent.
Not altogether unattractive.

204
00:17:22,123 --> 00:17:24,421
Yes, but will you be happy
being a hooker?

205
00:17:26,728 --> 00:17:30,425
The only jobs you consider me
qualified for are secretary and hooker.

206
00:17:30,732 --> 00:17:33,963
You're not qualified to be a secretary.

207
00:17:39,140 --> 00:17:41,005
What an interview.

208
00:17:41,276 --> 00:17:44,712
Don't take it too hard, honey.
It's only the first time.

209
00:17:44,879 --> 00:17:48,337
Take it too hard?
I start on Monday.

210
00:17:48,516 --> 00:17:50,279
That's wonderful.

211
00:18:23,618 --> 00:18:27,076
- The line ends after me, mister.
- Sorry.

212
00:18:31,793 --> 00:18:34,125
- That's a pretty nice suit, mister.
- Thank you.

213
00:18:34,295 --> 00:18:36,889
You've got some nerve
coming here dressed like that.

214
00:18:37,065 --> 00:18:40,865
People in here need this money.
This ain't no damn joy ride.

215
00:18:43,004 --> 00:18:46,667
Hey, you're Mr. Harper, aren't you?
Taft Aerospace.

216
00:18:46,841 --> 00:18:48,672
I'm Raoul Esteban. Remember?

217
00:18:48,843 --> 00:18:51,539
I was in the Taft Maintenance Division.
I used to do your office.

218
00:18:51,713 --> 00:18:54,375
- Sure, Raoul. Nice to see you.
- How you doing, man?

219
00:18:54,549 --> 00:18:56,813
Hey, they canned you too, huh?

220
00:18:56,985 --> 00:18:58,953
It's more complicated than that.

221
00:18:59,120 --> 00:19:00,917
- First time in here?
- Damn right.

222
00:19:01,089 --> 00:19:04,252
Man, are you in luck.
I'm gonna take care of you.

223
00:19:04,425 --> 00:19:07,053
- <i>Mi casa, su casa.</i> You know?
- Sure.

224
00:19:07,228 --> 00:19:09,253
First thing, you're in the wrong line.

225
00:19:09,430 --> 00:19:11,591
- Wrong line.
- I'm gonna lose my place here.

226
00:19:11,766 --> 00:19:13,961
Information, they make you wait
in line two hours.

227
00:19:14,135 --> 00:19:16,695
All they do is tell you
to fill out one of these.

228
00:19:16,871 --> 00:19:19,066
I'm gonna take care of you,
no problem.

229
00:19:23,645 --> 00:19:26,113
I'm going to have an operation
in a month.

230
00:19:26,281 --> 00:19:28,306
You know, the operation.

231
00:19:28,483 --> 00:19:32,078
And my analyst said I should
start making the adjustment.

232
00:19:32,253 --> 00:19:34,881
And, well, that's why they fired me.

233
00:19:35,056 --> 00:19:39,584
For wearing a most demure gray maxi
with a matching cashmere twin set.

234
00:19:39,761 --> 00:19:43,197
- It's here in the letter from my analyst.
- Let me check this out.

235
00:19:43,364 --> 00:19:45,696
Maybe we should pick another line,
what do you say?

236
00:19:45,867 --> 00:19:48,700
Listen, man, it's no sweat.
They ain't gonna hassle you.

237
00:19:48,870 --> 00:19:51,395
Look what your card says.
Aerospace executive.

238
00:19:51,572 --> 00:19:53,540
Yeah, but I'm not that anymore.

239
00:19:53,708 --> 00:19:56,233
In here, man, you are what you were.

